english:
  title: Essentials of the Nirvana Sutra
  author: Wonhyo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Consider the Way that is Nirvana: it is without way, yet nothing is outside the Way. It has no dwelling place, yet dwells everywhere. Thus we know this Way is at once infinitely near and infinitely far. Those who verify this Way grow ever more silent, yet grow ever more eloquent. In their eloquence, they sound the eight celestial tones, reverberating through the void without cessation. In their silence, they transcend the ten characteristics, resting in serene unity with the ultimate reality. Because it is infinitely far, one follows the teachings through a thousand kalpas yet never arrives. Because it is infinitely near, one forgets words and seeks it—yet finds it within a single moment of thought.

    This sutra is the great ocean of Buddhist dharma, the secret treasury of the Vaipulya teachings. Its meaning cannot be measured, for it is boundless in expanse and fathomless in depth. Because it is fathomless, nothing escapes its reach. Because it is boundless, nothing lies beyond its embrace. It gathers all scriptures into one unified flow, opens the Buddha's supreme impartiality, and harmonizes the disputes of a hundred schools. Thus all four kinds of beings return to the reality of non-duality, and all sentient minds awake to the ultimate fruit of enlightenment.

    This ultimate awakening embodies true nature while transcending discriminating mind. Since reality is non-dual, it merges the real and unreal into one. Yet if there is no duality, how can there be one? When the real and unreal merge, what remains as the real? Here intellect and reasoning both vanish, and all conceptual language ceases. This is the profound mystery of Nirvana. Yet the Buddhas realize this without abiding in it—they respond to all without exception, they speak to all without limit. This is the supreme teaching of Nirvana. The mystery is present yet never silent; the teaching speaks yet never speaks. This is the unified flavor of principle and teaching.

    Those who hear even a single syllable receive benefit to their very pores. Those who seek even half a verse fear not the shattering of their bones. The sinners who have committed grave transgressions find their karma erased through faith in this sutra. The spiritually severed find their spiritual roots restored through reliance on this teaching.

    The term "Mahaparinirvana"—if we render it in the Sanskrit tongue of the Western lands, we say "Mahaparinirvana"—is translated in this land as "Great Extinction and Deliverance." To illuminate the Way that the Tathagata realizes: its substance pervades all without exterior limit, its function extends universally through all sentience. In its encompassing care and far-reaching salvation, nothing surpasses it. Because nothing comes before it, we call it "Great." Its substance and function are non-dual, without distinction. There is no far shore to reach, no near shore to leave. Because there is nothing to leave, there is nothing that is not left behind—thus is it "Great Extinction." Because there is nothing to reach, there is nothing that is not reached—thus is it "Great Deliverance." For these reasons it is called "Great Extinction and Deliverance."

    The "Sutra" is the supreme utterance of the Great Sage, conveying one principle through myriad forms, unchanging through countless ages. It is called a sutra because it is dharma beyond impermanence. Before the main teaching is presented, events are first recounted—hence it is called "The First Chapter of the Preface."
  footnotes:
    - The eight celestial tones (八音) refer to the eight sounds or ways in which the Buddha's voice manifests
    - The ten characteristics (十相) represent fundamental conceptual categories that bind sentient beings to conditioned existence
    - The four kinds of beings (四生) traditionally include those born from wombs, eggs, moisture, and transformation
    - The phrase about hearing a syllable and seeking half a verse alludes to the immeasurable benefits of the dharma and the willingness to sacrifice everything for spiritual truth
